                  </table>
                  <h5> <a name="gov"></a>Government </h5>
                  <p>Under the Noumea Accord of May 1998, New Caledonia has its 
                    own special status within the French constitution. The Accord 
                    sets up a timetable for the gradual transfer of responsibilities 
                    from France to the Territory. At the end of a transitional 
                    period of twelve years, the only powers left to France will 
                    involve the justice system, public order, currency, defence 
                    and foreign affairs (outside of the region). The Noumea Accord 
                    also created a Caledonian 'citizenship'. Between 2013 and 
                    2018, a referendum will be put to the population of the territory 
                    (restricted to people who have resided there for at least 
                    20 years) to decide if it wants to assume these remaining 
                    responsibilities and become fully independent. 
                  <p>The Territory is administered by a Congress made up of 54 
                    members elected by popular vote for a five year term. The 
                    Congress elects in turn a 'collegial' government under a proportional 
                    system, aimed at ensuring that more than one party makes up 
                    the executive. 
                  <p>New Caledonia is represented in the French parliament by 
                    two deputies and one senator. 
                  <p>The Territory is divided into three provinces each with its own Assembly and local executive. The Noumea Accord also provides for an Economic and Social Committee which has an advisory role, and a Custom Senate, which advises the Government on matters affecting the indigenous Kanak community.


                  <h5><b><a name="res"></a></b>Resources </h5>
                  <p>As New Caledonia owns around one quarter of the world's known 
                    deposits of nickel, nickel mining is the main source of revenue. 
                    The economy of the territory is therefore dependent on the 
                    fluctuations of the price of nickel on the international market. 
                    The Territory's only processing plant is located in Noumea, 
                    but a new smelter is planned for the north of the main island 
                    with the aim of achieving a better balance between the Southern 
                    Province (where most of the wealth is concentrated) and the 
                    rest of the country. 
                  <p>Traditional agriculture is practised widely amongst Kanak communities mainly in the north of the mainland and in the islands. 

                  <p>Coffee and copra are the main agricultural exports, while cattle stations on 
                    the west coast satisfy most of the local demand in meat. 
                  <p>Tourism has become an important source of revenue despite the high local cost of living compared with other Pacific tourist destinations. 

                  <p>Financial aid provided by France accounts for 20% of the territory's GDP, mainly 
                    to cover expenditure on health, education and the public service. 
                    <br>
                    <br>
                  <h5><a name="hist"></a>History </h5>
                  <p>New Caledonia was settled by successive waves of migration 
                    dating back many hundreds of years before European colonisation. 
                    The land was divided between distinct communities each with 
                    their own language. In mountainous areas, Kanak tribes practised 
                    a sophisticated form of taro farming, using irrigated, contoured 
                    terraces. 
                  <p>Captain James Cook named the main island (after the Latin 
                    name for Scotland) after landing on the northern coast in 
                    1774. The first missionaries from the London Missionary Society 
                    and the Marist Brothers arrived in the 1840s. The French took 
                    possession of the island in 1853, officially to protect the 
                    French missionaries but in effect to counteract the growing 
                    British influence in the region. From 1864 to 1897, New Caledonia 
                    became a penal colony, receiving 40,000 transported prisoners. 
                  <p>The discovery of huge nickel deposits in 1863 accelerated the process of colonisation. The displacement of villages which were occupying new mine sites and the encroachment of the settlers' cattle on Kanak gardens provoked several rebellions. The main one was led by Chief Ataï in 1878. All were violently suppressed by the French authorities. 

                  <p>From 1942, New Caledonia was transformed into an important 
                    US military base. The post-war period saw a rise in pro-independence 
                    sentiment amongst the indigenous Kanaks (representing about 
                    44% of the total population) and a parallel push against independence, 
                    mainly from the non-indigenous population. The antagonism 
                    between the two groups culminated in the events of 1984 when 
                    barricades were erected in Noumea and several pro-independence 
                    Kanak leaders were killed. Following another bloody confrontation 
                    in 1988 (during which 19 Kanaks and 6 gendarmes were killed), 
                    the leaders of the opposite camps signed the Matignon Accords 
                    which paved the way for a ten year period of political calm. 
                  <p>During this time the economic imbalance between mainly European 
                    Noumea and the Southern Province, and the rest of the country 
                    was to be addressed. A referendum on independence which was 
                    due to take place in 1998 was postponed to at least 2013 following 
                    the signing of a new political agreement - the Noumea Accord 
                    - in May 1998. 
                  <p>The new accord provides for the gradual transfer of responsibilities from France to New Caledonia over 15 to 20 years (with the exception of the 'regalian' powers i.e. justice, defence, foreign affairs, public order).

                  <h5>Main Issues </h5>
                  <ul>
                    <li> 
                      <p>lack of economic diversity </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <p>persistent imbalance between a wealthy, mainly European, 
                        Southern Province and the rest of the country, where most 
                        of the Kanak population lives</p>
                    </li>
                  </ul>
